node_modules/mongodb/README.md:100:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:101:#### Typescript Version
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:102:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:103:We recommend using the latest version of typescript, however we currently ensure the driver's public types compile against `typescript@5.6.0`.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:104:This is the lowest typescript version guaranteed to work with our driver: older versions may or may not work - use at your own risk.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:105:Since typescript [does not restrict breaking changes to major versions](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/wiki/Breaking-Changes), we consider this support best effort.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:106:If you run into any unexpected compiler failures against our supported TypeScript versions, please let us know by filing an issue on our [JIRA](https://jira.mongodb.org/browse/NODE).
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:107:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:108:Additionally, our Typescript types are compatible with the ECMAScript standard for our minimum supported Node version. Currently, our Typescript targets es2023.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:109:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:110:#### Running in Custom Runtimes
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:111:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:112:We are working on removing Node.js as a dependency of the driver, so that in the future it will be possible to use the driver in non-Node environments.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:113:This work is currently in progress, and if you're curious, this is [our first runtime adapter commit](https://github.com/mongodb/node-mongodb-native/commit/d2ad07f20903d86334da81222a6df9717f76faaa).
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:114:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:115:Some things to keep in mind if you are using a non-Node runtime:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:116:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:117:1. Users of Webpack/Vite may need to prevent `crypto` polyfill injection.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:118:2. Auth mechanism `SCRAM-SHA-1` has a hard dependency on Node.js.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:119:3. Auth mechanism `SCRAM-SHA-1` is not supported in FIPS mode.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:120:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:121:## Installation
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:122:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:123:The recommended way to get started using the Node.js driver is by using the `npm` (Node Package Manager) to install the dependency in your project.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:124:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:125:After you've created your own project using `npm init`, you can run:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:126:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:127:```bash
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:128:npm install mongodb
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:129:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:130:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:131:This will download the MongoDB driver and add a dependency entry in your `package.json` file.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:132:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:133:If you are a Typescript user, you will need the Node.js type definitions to use the driver's definitions:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:134:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:135:```sh
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:136:npm install -D @types/node
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:137:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:138:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:139:## Driver Extensions
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:140:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:141:The MongoDB driver can optionally be enhanced by the following feature packages:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:142:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:143:Maintained by MongoDB:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:144:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:145:- Zstd network compression - [@mongodb-js/zstd](https://github.com/mongodb-js/zstd)
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:146:- MongoDB field level and queryable encryption - [mongodb-client-encryption](https://github.com/mongodb/libmongocrypt#readme)
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:147:- GSSAPI / SSPI / Kerberos authentication - [kerberos](https://github.com/mongodb-js/kerberos)
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:148:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:149:Some of these packages include native C++ extensions.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:150:Consult the [trouble shooting guide here](https://github.com/mongodb/node-mongodb-native/blob/HEAD/etc/notes/native-extensions.md) if you run into compilation issues.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:151:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:152:Third party:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:153:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:154:- Snappy network compression - [snappy](https://github.com/Brooooooklyn/snappy)
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:155:- AWS authentication - [@aws-sdk/credential-providers](https://github.com/aws/aws-sdk-js-v3/tree/main/packages/credential-providers)
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:156:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:157:## Quick Start
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:158:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:159:This guide will show you how to set up a simple application using Node.js and MongoDB. Its scope is only how to set up the driver and perform the simple CRUD operations. For more in-depth coverage, see the [official documentation](https://www.mongodb.com/docs/drivers/node/).
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:160:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:161:### Create the `package.json` file
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:162:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:163:First, create a directory where your application will live.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:164:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:165:```bash
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:166:mkdir myProject
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:167:cd myProject
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:168:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:169:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:170:Enter the following command and answer the questions to create the initial structure for your new project:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:171:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:172:```bash
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:173:npm init -y
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:174:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:175:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:176:Next, install the driver as a dependency.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:177:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:178:```bash
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:179:npm install mongodb
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:180:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:181:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:182:### Start a MongoDB Server
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:183:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:184:For complete MongoDB installation instructions, see [the manual](https://www.mongodb.com/docs/manual/installation/).
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:185:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:186:1. Download the right MongoDB version from [MongoDB](https://www.mongodb.org/downloads)
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:187:2. Create a database directory (in this case under **/data**).
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:188:3. Install and start a `mongod` process.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:189:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:190:```bash
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:191:mongod --dbpath=/data
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:192:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:193:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:194:You should see the **mongod** process start up and print some status information.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:195:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:196:### Connect to MongoDB
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:197:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:198:Create a new **app.js** file and add the following code to try out some basic CRUD
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:199:operations using the MongoDB driver.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:200:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:201:Add code to connect to the server and the database **myProject**:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:202:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:203:> **NOTE:** Resolving DNS Connection issues
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:204:>
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:205:> Node.js 18 changed the default DNS resolution ordering from always prioritizing IPv4 to the ordering
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:206:> returned by the DNS provider. In some environments, this can result in `localhost` resolving to
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:207:> an IPv6 address instead of IPv4 and a consequent failure to connect to the server.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:208:>
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:209:> This can be resolved by:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:210:>
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:211:> - specifying the IP address family using the MongoClient `family` option (`MongoClient(<uri>, { family: 4 } )`)
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:212:> - launching mongod or mongos with the ipv6 flag enabled ([--ipv6 mongod option documentation](https://www.mongodb.com/docs/manual/reference/program/mongod/#std-option-mongod.--ipv6))
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:213:> - using a host of `127.0.0.1` in place of localhost
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:214:> - specifying the DNS resolution ordering with the `--dns-resolution-order` Node.js command line argument (e.g. `node --dns-resolution-order=ipv4first`)
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:215:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:216:```js
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:217:const { MongoClient } = require('mongodb');
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:218:// or as an es module:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:219:// import { MongoClient } from 'mongodb'
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:220:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:221:// Connection URL
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:222:const url = 'mongodb://localhost:27017';
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:223:const client = new MongoClient(url);
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:224:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:225:// Database Name
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:226:const dbName = 'myProject';
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:227:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:228:async function main() {
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:229:  // Use connect method to connect to the server
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:230:  await client.connect();
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:231:  console.log('Connected successfully to server');
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:232:  const db = client.db(dbName);
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:233:  const collection = db.collection('documents');
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:234:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:235:  // the following code examples can be pasted here...
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:236:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:237:  return 'done.';
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:238:}
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:239:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:240:main()
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:241:  .then(console.log)
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:242:  .catch(console.error)
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:243:  .finally(() => client.close());
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:244:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:245:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:246:Run your app from the command line with:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:247:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:248:```bash
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:249:node app.js
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:250:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:251:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:252:The application should print **Connected successfully to server** to the console.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:253:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:254:### Insert a Document
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:255:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:256:Add to **app.js** the following function which uses the **insertMany**
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:257:method to add three documents to the **documents** collection.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:258:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:259:```js
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:260:const insertResult = await collection.insertMany([{ a: 1 }, { a: 2 }, { a: 3 }]);
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:261:console.log('Inserted documents =>', insertResult);
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:262:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:263:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:264:The **insertMany** command returns an object with information about the insert operations.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:265:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:266:### Find All Documents
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:267:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:268:Add a query that returns all the documents.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:269:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:270:```js
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:271:const findResult = await collection.find({}).toArray();
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:272:console.log('Found documents =>', findResult);
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:273:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:274:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:275:This query returns all the documents in the **documents** collection.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:276:If you add this below the insertMany example, you'll see the documents you've inserted.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:277:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:278:### Find Documents with a Query Filter
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:279:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:280:Add a query filter to find only documents which meet the query criteria.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:281:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:282:```js
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:283:const filteredDocs = await collection.find({ a: 3 }).toArray();
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:284:console.log('Found documents filtered by { a: 3 } =>', filteredDocs);
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:285:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:286:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:287:Only the documents which match `'a' : 3` should be returned.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:288:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:289:### Update a document
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:290:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:291:The following operation updates a document in the **documents** collection.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:292:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:293:```js
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:294:const updateResult = await collection.updateOne({ a: 3 }, { $set: { b: 1 } });
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:295:console.log('Updated documents =>', updateResult);
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:296:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:297:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:298:The method updates the first document where the field **a** is equal to **3** by adding a new field **b** to the document set to **1**. `updateResult` contains information about whether there was a matching document to update or not.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:299:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:300:### Remove a document
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:301:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:302:Remove the document where the field **a** is equal to **3**.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:303:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:304:```js
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:305:const deleteResult = await collection.deleteMany({ a: 3 });
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:306:console.log('Deleted documents =>', deleteResult);
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:307:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:308:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:309:### Index a Collection
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:310:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:311:[Indexes](https://www.mongodb.com/docs/manual/indexes/) can improve your application's
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:312:performance. The following function creates an index on the **a** field in the
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:313:**documents** collection.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:314:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:315:```js
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:316:const indexName = await collection.createIndex({ a: 1 });
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:317:console.log('index name =', indexName);
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:318:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:319:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:320:For more detailed information, see the [indexing strategies page](https://www.mongodb.com/docs/manual/applications/indexes/).
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:321:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:322:## Error Handling
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:323:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:324:If you need to filter certain errors from our driver, we have a helpful tree of errors described in [etc/notes/errors.md](https://github.com/mongodb/node-mongodb-native/blob/HEAD/etc/notes/errors.md).
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:325:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:326:It is our recommendation to use `instanceof` checks on errors and to avoid relying on parsing `error.message` and `error.name` strings in your code.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:327:We guarantee `instanceof` checks will pass according to semver guidelines, but errors may be sub-classed or their messages may change at any time, even patch releases, as we see fit to increase the helpfulness of the errors.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:328:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:329:Any new errors we add to the driver will directly extend an existing error class and no existing error will be moved to a different parent class outside of a major release.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:330:This means `instanceof` will always be able to accurately capture the errors that our driver throws.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:331:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:332:```typescript
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:333:const client = new MongoClient(url);
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:334:await client.connect();
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:335:const collection = client.db().collection('collection');
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:336:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:337:try {
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:338:  await collection.insertOne({ _id: 1 });
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:339:  await collection.insertOne({ _id: 1 }); // duplicate key error
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:340:} catch (error) {
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:341:  if (error instanceof MongoServerError) {
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:342:    console.log(`Error worth logging: ${error}`); // special case for some reason
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:343:  }
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:344:  throw error; // still want to crash
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:345:}
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:346:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:347:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:348:## Nightly releases
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:349:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:350:If you need to test with a change from the latest `main` branch, our `mongodb` npm package has nightly versions released under the `nightly` tag.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:351:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:352:```sh
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:353:npm install mongodb@nightly
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:354:```
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:355:
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:356:Nightly versions are published regardless of testing outcome.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:357:This means there could be semantic breakages or partially implemented features.
node_modules/mongodb/README.md:358:The nightly build is not suitable for production use.
